TASK: Code Quality Review — Plan 1 Task 5: XP & Badge System

SESSION: 2026-03-19 (Code Review Phase)

REVIEW SCOPE:
  Files reviewed: js/xp.js (253 lines), tests/index.html, tests/test-xp.js, tests/test-persona.js
  Base SHA: f1bb483 | Head SHA: 541d0f8
  Plan reference: docs/superpowers/plans/2026-03-19-cyberspark-plan1-foundation.md, Task 5

OVERALL ASSESSMENT: APPROVED WITH REQUIRED FIXES
  Implementation is fundamentally correct and plan-aligned.
  One important issue must be resolved before Task 6 proceeds.
  Two suggestions recommended for implementation robustness.

PLAN ALIGNMENT: 100%
  - All 17 badges implemented exactly as specified
  - XP_AWARDS table matches spec (15 entries, all correct values)
  - Public API matches spec exactly (awardXP, getXP, getBadges, hasBadge, checkBadges, BADGE_REGISTRY)
  - localStorage key naming: all 15 keys use cyberspark_ prefix consistently
  - Test harness matches spec HTML exactly
  - 8 tests match spec test-xp.js exactly
  - test-persona.js placeholder present as specified

ISSUES FOUND:

  IMPORTANT (must fix before Task 6 proceeds):
  1. cyber_champion uses positional slice(0,-1) instead of id filter
     File: js/xp.js line 198
     Current: const otherIds = BADGE_REGISTRY.slice(0,-1).map(b => b.id);
     Risk: If any developer appends a new badge after cyber_champion, the badge
           silently becomes included in cyber_champion's requirement list,
           AND cyber_champion itself would no longer be excluded from its own check.
           This fails silently with no error. In a gamification system, silent
           badge logic errors are high-severity because students lose trust.
     Recommended fix: filter by id !== 'cyber_champion' instead of positional slice.

  SUGGESTIONS (nice to have, do not block Task 6):

  2. awardXP does not guard against NaN input
     File: js/xp.js line 41
     Current guard: if (amount <= 0) return;
     Issue: NaN <= 0 evaluates to false in JavaScript, so NaN passes the guard.
            localStorage.setItem('cyberspark_xp', String(NaN)) stores 'NaN'.
            getXP() then returns NaN from parseInt('NaN', 10).
            All subsequent XP math silently produces NaN.
     Context: Low real-world risk since all callers use XP_AWARDS constants,
              but should be hardened for Plan 2+ game modules that may pass
              computed scores.
     Recommended fix: add isNaN(amount) check to the guard condition.

  3. Toast removal relies on animationend event
     File: js/xp.js lines 239-241
     Issue: If CSS animations are disabled (prefers-reduced-motion, browser settings,
            or animation CSS not loaded), animationend never fires and the toast
            element is never removed from the DOM.
     Context: Minor UI issue; does not affect XP/badge state correctness.
     Recommended fix: add a fallback setTimeout(toast.remove, 500) after the
                      classList.add('dismissing') call.

RECURSION SAFETY: VERIFIED SAFE
  Call chain: awardXP -> checkBadges -> _grantBadge -> awardXP (recursive)
  Termination guarantee: _grantBadge writes badge to localStorage BEFORE calling
  awardXP, so hasBadge() guard at top of _grantBadge prevents re-entry for the
  same badge. Maximum recursion depth is bounded by badge count (17).
  _buildState() re-reads localStorage on each recursive call — no stale state.
  Assessment: recursion is bounded and safe as implemented.

TEST COVERAGE GAPS (not blocking, but should be filled during or after Task 6):
  - hasBadge() returning TRUE for an earned badge (only false case tested)
  - checkBadges() actually granting a badge end-to-end
  - awardXP rejecting amount <= 0
  - cyber_champion unlock logic validation
  - awardPromptCopyXP 10-call session cap
  - markPageVisited awarding XP for non-index pages
  - markPageVisited NOT awarding XP for index.html
  - markPageVisited deduplication (no double-award on repeat visit)
  Currently: 8 tests cover 8 happy-path scenarios only.

